            "content": "Race: Cherikin (grimdark lore)\nRace definition: {\n  Size: Small, Angel-like (mini wings)\n\n  Race features:\n\n  Gliding \n    Mechanical: 80 ft Gliding, 5 ft drop, No heavy or medium armor. - 10d6 damage if the Cherikin manage to fly into something. \n    \"Some creatures or vehicles are powered simply by the aerodynamics of their shape and possess no ability to maintain altitude.\n    These creatures/objects possess a glide speed.\"\n    A gliding creature/vehicle falls at minimum by 5 feet every turn and must move their full glide speed (horizontal/diving).\n    The creature/pilot can choose to dive by converting horizontal movement into downward movement.\n    It's possible to reduce the Fall and Movement-speed to 0 for one round, but that ends the flight.\n    A creature has to fall at least 10 feet to be able to enter Glide.\n    (nerfed 5e Variant Rule)\n    Lore of the wings: Wings have made it easier to deploy the Cherikin.\n    The wings are there to bring the Cherikin _down_,\n    a biological Parachute/glider.\n    No need to bring a teleport-circle to the ground.\n    Just drop them into the air – they will find their landing spot on their own. Maybe.)\n\n  Scatterbrain:\n    Mechanical: Advantage against Possession, disadvantage on Intelligence (History) checks until you possess a diary (empty book) in your inventory.\n    \"Your ruptured spirit makes it harder to influence your mind but you have trouble to remember.\"\n    \n    Lore: Built-in feature to make the Cherikin immune to PTSD and reduce downtime.\n    They are built to forget things fast.\n    Your diary (a simple empty book where you can write down important things) reduces this, but does not remove the condition itself.\n    (Without the book, they forget even the mission by noon.)\n    (You will forget even your comrades after a while if you have not written them in your diary → see Lemming’s Deathwish.)    \n    Additionally, your fleeting memory prevents you from mourning or grasping the absence of others;\n    you cannot recall the details of a creature after 24 hours of absence.\n\n  ADHS:\n    Mechanical: +3 initiative; -1 Charisma in social, -1 Intelligence in social encounters\n    \"You have the energy of a hamster on amphetamines. Always.\"\n    Lore: Since the Cherikin is made to be in an environment where every second counts, a Cherikin has to be fast and on alert. Always. What is useful on a battlefield is more than a hindrance in daily life during peace.\n\n  A Lemming’s Deathwish:\n    Mechanical: You have advantage on saving throws against being frightened, have disadvantage on Wisdom (Perception) or Intelligence (Investigation) checks to detect traps or hazards.\n    \"You don’t fear death – not because you are brave, but because your race doesn’t know the concept of death.\"\n    Lore: Since the Demons have used Fear, and a soldier who gets frightened on a battlefield is a dead soldier, Cherikin are not made to feel fear.\n    At all.\n    As you fail to recognize the consequences of environmental dangers.\n\n  Cuteness:\n    A Cherikin gets +2 to Charisma but has disadvantage on Intimidation checks.\n\n  Free ASI:\n    You gain another +1 that can be freely chosen (even Charisma).\n\n  Collared (Non serviam): \n    To remove the collar, a Cherikin needs a DC 30 Wisdom check.\n    Lore: With the \"removal of the collar\" – a Cherikin can lay down its collar whenever it's commanded to, is not meant to simply \"lay down the collar\", it's the moment of its \"Non serviam\" – the moment a Cherikin _decides_ to be free. \n    (Since D&D doesn’t support a \"willpower\" stat, the Wisdom stat is the nearest to that.) \n    (Flavor: the collars have a small lock on its back, no special check to open it. – Sometimes some Cherikin have put down their collar absent-mindedly to scratch on its neck, and have forgotten it afterwards – yes, they are that stupid – so the angels have decided to lock the collars with a small small lock.)\n\n  Clicker-trained:\n    To withstand a \"clicker\" command, a Cherikin must succeed on a DC 20 Wisdom saving throw (the more dangerous a situation, the lower the check – the DM can lower this check situationally but not increase it over DC 20).\n    Lore: The battle-conditioning of a Cherikin allows it to ignore clicker commands in the heat of battle.\n\n  Collar Conditioning:\n    To remove something attached to the collar, a Cherikin must succeed on a DC 20 Wisdom check (the more dangerous a situation, the lower the check – the DM can lower this check situationally but not increase it over DC 20).\n    Lore: Since sometimes something is attached to the collar, and a situation demands to remove it, a Cherikin is still able to remove it. – It's difficult to fight against the training, but not impossible.\n\n  Non serviam: After a successful removal of the collar in a \"Non serviam\" moment, a Cherikin is \"free\".\n    For the Celestial Realm itself, a Cherikin who breaks free is officially a \"not my problem\" thing anymore, but that doesn’t necessarily mean that the singular owner (angel) behaves that way. (DM discretion) (from \"it has found its free will – finally – I help it to survive\" to \"why, was my care not good enough for ya?\" – \"lost pet-flyers\" – to \"try to lure them back\" – or \"what rightfully is mine\" → the independent angel can act differently – the reaction isn’t illegal – doesn’t matter which one – but it's not state-backed)\n\n  Tldr: Cherikin are made with ADHS – on purpose – to hyperfocus during battle. \n  They are made for the battlefield; everything else was secondary at best.\n  Angels have kept them as pets _because_ outside of a battlefield they are childish, overexcited and so on → useless.\n\n  Exemption:\n    Not every Cherikin is a pet – There are some groups outside of the eternal realm that are independent; they managed to break free from their collars. But it’s unlikely to see them.\n    The fearless behavior, forgetfulness make them very vulnerable outside of the celestial realm.\n    It’s uncommon to see an uncollared and untrained Cherikin.\n\n  Lore:\n    During the great war – Heaven against Hell – the angels needed a cheap front-line soldier:\n    Cheap, fearless, easy to train, fast reaction time, easy to deploy.\n    So they decided to create the Cherikin.\n    The result of that program exceeded expectations.\n    It created the Cherikins – a cheap, reliable race of disposable front soldiers.\n    Their purpose was to be disposable shock troops.\n    Thrown in the first wave, don’t ask questions, charge without fear, and forget everything afterwards.\n    Bad old times. But Heaven won in the end.\n\n    → Tldr: Cherikin are made with ADHS – on purpose – to hyperfocus during battle. \n    → They are made for the battlefield; everything else was secondary at best.\n\n    After the war, as peace took over, the Cherikin lost their purpose.\n    They needed another task to fulfill.\n\n    Sometimes an angel decided to need assistance for bureaucratic duties and chose Cherikins to help.\n    Later on, the angels found out that this race – even if good-aligned and helpful –\n    wasn’t really useful in their chaotic approach, and they forget things. Fast.\n\n    The energy of a hamster on speed, the scatterbrain of a bird/goldfish,\n    the short attention span, childlike behavior, and the \"catch shiny things\" instinct of a cat\n    make them more of a burden than a helpful asset.\n    But they are too cute to abandon, so some angels decided to keep them as pets.\n\n    It’s common that a Cherikin has received \"clicker training\" – for simple commands like \"sit\",\n    and a \"don’t remove the thing that is attached to your collar\" conditioning.\n\n    → Angels have kept them as pets _because_ outside of a battlefield they are childish, overexcited and so on → useless. \n    → You can’t let roam \"murder-hamsters\" freely without control, without leash. That way the angels kept them under control. (And have got a pet)\n}\n",
